## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests. 0 real verifications.** This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called in declaration order, but almost nothing is actually asserted. These tests will hit 95%+ line coverage while catching approximately zero bugs.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 7 |
| 🟠 High | 1 |
| 🟡 Medium | 2 |

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic — entire class)

The class methodically calls every method on `ProductCatalog` with no meaningful assertions. 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; the other 4 use only `Assert.IsNotNull()` on types that can never be null (`List<T>`, `string`).

**Tests with no assertions at all:**

| Test (line) | What it misses |
|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` (L17) | Never checks the product was actually stored |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` (L33) | Never checks the price changed. A no-op `UpdatePrice` passes. |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` (L39) | Never checks the product was actually deleted |
| `GetProductCount_Works` (L63) | Never checks the count value — doesn't even capture the return |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (L69) | Never checks any price was reduced. A 100% discount or 0% discount both pass. |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` (L85) | Never checks any product was imported |

**Fix example — `AddProduct_Works` (L17):**
```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verifies the product is retrievable with correct data
var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

**Fix example — `UpdatePrice_Works` (L33):**
```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
```

**Fix example — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (L69):**
```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// AFTER
